  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Thinking e-Residency Equals Residence</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">This is the most common misconception. e-Residency is a digital identity for business purposes—it gives you ZERO rights to live, work, or travel in Estonia or the EU. If you want to physically reside in Estonia, you need a separate visa or residence permit.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Access to Haigekassa (Public Healthcare)</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Freelancers, e-Residents, and Digital Nomad Visa holders do not automatically get Haigekassa access. You must have private insurance. The only workaround is paying yourself a salary and social tax through an OÜ company—which adds significant complexity.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Planning to Renew the Digital Nomad Visa</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The DN Visa is explicitly non-renewable. After 1 year, you must leave or switch to a different permit type (like Self-Employed TRP). Plan your long-term residency strategy from the start, not at month 11.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Accounting Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Estonian OÜ companies require proper bookkeeping and annual filings. While Estonia's 0% retained earnings tax is attractive, you still need monthly VAT reports (if applicable), annual accounts, and compliance. Budget €50-150/month for accounting services.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring the Winter Reality</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Estonian winters are dark and cold—Tallinn gets about 6 hours of daylight in December, with temperatures often below -10°C. If you're from a warm climate, this isn't a minor adjustment. Many nomads leave during winter or struggle with seasonal depression.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

